the safe fix rule
Globular Distributed-System Pattern Catalog
0. Prime directive

The system must act only on validated, current, complete, durable truth.

If a control path uses truth that is:

stale
partial
inferred
non-durable
unverified

then assume a bug is possible.

1. Persistence Gap
Definition

State changes in memory but does not become durable.

Detect

Look for:

field updated
map updated
struct mutated
but no etcd write / persistStateLocked() / saveState() / durable commit
Code smell
x = newValue with no persistence call after
persistence error ignored
background goroutines launched before durable write succeeds
Failure mode
restart loses truth
leader failover sees different truth
memory and etcd diverge
Fix rule

Every state mutation that matters to control flow must cross a persistence barrier or fail.

Typical fix
update state
persist
check error
only then trigger side effects
2. Error Swallowing
Definition

An error happens, but the code reports success or suppresses recovery.

Detect

Look for:

return nil in failure branch
ignored err
log-only failure in control path
if err != nil { log... } but continue as healthy
Failure mode
rediscovery never triggers
retries never happen
health appears good while logic is broken
Fix rule

Errors that affect control decisions must propagate into the loop that can react.

Typical fix
return real error
set degraded/unreachable state
trigger retry / rediscovery / rollback
3. Stale Authority
Definition

A component keeps using an old leader, endpoint, owner, or routing decision.

Detect

Look for:

cached endpoint
cached client
leader address stored once
refresh only when empty, not when unhealthy
multiple independent dial paths
Failure mode
heartbeats sent to dead leader
client talks to old controller
node stays connected to obsolete authority
Fix rule

Authority must be refreshed when unhealthy, not only when missing.

Typical fix
rediscover on degraded/unreachable
reset client on endpoint change
persist new authority after successful switch
unify dial paths
4. Identity Truncation
Definition

A richer identity exists, but control logic uses only part of it.

Detect

Look for version-only comparisons where true identity should include:

name
version
build number
platform
checksum
Code smell
installed == version
map[string]string for desired versions
rollback keyed only by version
preview logic using version-only equality
Failure mode
wrong build treated as healthy
wrong rollback target chosen
same-version hotfix not deployed
Fix rule

All control paths must use canonical identity, never partial identity.

Canonical identity

At minimum:

service name
version
build number
checksum if available
Typical fix

Use a struct, not loose strings:

type CanonicalIdentity struct {
    Name        string
    Version     string
    BuildNumber int64
    Checksum    string
    Platform    string
}
5. CAS / LWT Ignored
Definition

A conditional write is attempted, but code does not verify whether it actually applied.

Detect

Look for:

Scylla/Cassandra IF ...
compare-and-set semantics
.Exec() on conditional query
no applied check
Failure mode
lease ownership silently lost
stale owner continues acting
double execution
inconsistent lock semantics
Fix rule

Every conditional write must check whether it applied.

Typical fix

Use ScanCAS(...) or equivalent and branch on applied == false.

6. Ownership Without Proof
Definition

Code releases, modifies, or finalizes a resource without proving it still owns it.

Detect

Look for:

delete/update by run_id only
no executor_id, no owner token, no epoch check
release path less strict than acquire path
Failure mode
old executor deletes new owner’s lease
stale controller finalizes a release it no longer owns
split-brain side effects
Fix rule

Acquire, heartbeat, and release must all prove ownership with the same identity.

Typical fix
DELETE ... IF executor_id = ?
ownership tokens / epochs
reject stale releasers
7. Non-Atomic Control Decision
Definition

Code reads current state, then acts later, assuming nothing changed in between.

Detect

Look for:

SELECT / count / exists
then insert/update later
no lock, no LWT, no compare-and-swap
Failure mode
duplicate workflow runs
duplicate day-0 import
two leaders think they’re first
two actors both “see nothing” and proceed
Fix rule

Critical uniqueness and idempotency decisions must be atomic.

Typical fix
LWT-backed claim
lock row
IF NOT EXISTS
correlation lock table
8. Fake Recovery Truth
Definition

During recovery, the system invents values it does not truly know.

Detect

Look for:

default roles
default profiles
fabricated node type
assumed readiness
implicit “must be control-plane”
Failure mode
worker becomes control-plane by accident
routing, successor selection, or desired-state filtering gets poisoned
Fix rule

Unknown must stay unknown until proven.

Typical fix

Use:

Profiles: []string{"unknown"}
Status: "recovering"

and suppress privileged actions until truth is re-established.

9. Weak Success Predicate
Definition

The system accepts a condition as success even though it is only a shallow proxy.

Detect

Look for:

“unit exists” instead of “service healthy”
“leader address changed” instead of “new leader is ready”
“version matches” instead of “canonical identity matches”
Failure mode
rollout marked complete too early
successor chosen but not truly ready
health looks green while service is half-dead
Fix rule

Success must mean operationally ready, not merely structurally present.

Typical fix

Strengthen predicate with:

readiness bit
healthy service state
exact build match
control-plane capability proven
10. Unsafe Leadership
Definition

Leadership changes without safe successor, reachable publication, or readiness guarantees.

Detect

Look for:

resign without successor
successor eligibility too weak
publish leader address failure treated as log-only
single-node resignation loops
Failure mode
invisible leader
election loops
failover to dead or stale controller
cluster-wide confusion
Fix rule

Leadership requires valid successor, published reachability, and readiness.

Typical fix
do not resign unless successor exists and is healthy
leadership publish failure should degrade or resign
single-node clusters must not self-destruct
11. Unsafe Remediation
Definition

A repair loop acts without checking whether the action is admissible.

Detect

Look for:

blind restart loops
retries without backoff or terminal blocked state
remediation that ignores dependency graph
Failure mode
endless restart storms
dependent services flapping
damage amplification
Fix rule

Remediation must have admission rules.

Typical fix

Before restart/retry:

verify dependency health
bound attempts
mark blocked after threshold
emit explicit degraded state
12. False Equivalence
Definition

Two states are treated as equivalent when they are not.

Detect

Look for:

unreachable treated as drift
stale applied hash treated as fresh installed truth
same version treated as same artifact
desired state compared without node profile filtering
Failure mode
false drift
false health
false no-op
rollout skipped when needed
Fix rule

Comparison must use correct freshness, scope, and identity.

Typical fix

Distinguish:

unreachable
stale
unknown
mismatched
exact match
13. Split Truth
Definition

Different subsystems derive the same fact from different sources or paths.

Detect

Look for:

one path uses etcd
another uses in-memory cache
another re-dials independently
another uses --describe
another uses installed-state
Failure mode
two components disagree while both look locally correct
debugging becomes nonlinear
one path heals while another keeps failing
Fix rule

Each class of truth must have one source of authority.

Typical fix

Examples:

leader endpoint from one canonical channel
installed artifact truth from installed-state
version/build identity from manifest + installed-state, not ad hoc strings
14. Background Side Effects Before Durability
Definition

Secondary actions run before the primary state is durably committed.

Detect

Look for:

goroutine launch after state mutation but before persist success
enqueue, projection, publish, reconcile triggers before durable write
Failure mode
background loops observe half-written truth
racey flaps after recovery or leader handoff
Fix rule

Persist first, then fan out side effects.

15. Good-Enough Fallback That Reintroduces the Bug
Definition

A strict path falls back to a weaker path “for convenience.”

Detect

Look for:

“if etcd missing, accept version-only”
“if identity incomplete, compare semantic version only”
“if publish fails, continue leader anyway”
Failure mode
exactness disappears in degraded conditions
bug only appears under stress or lag
same bug resurfaces as a “temporary fallback”
Fix rule

In control paths, missing proof must fail closed, not degrade to weaker truth.

16. Multiple Dial Paths
Definition

The same target service is reached through different client creation logic.

Detect

Look for:

helper creates raw grpc.NewClient(...)
main path uses cached client with rediscovery
side path dials directly from endpoint string
Failure mode
main path healthy, side path stale
hostname sync or admin path fails while heartbeats work
Fix rule

Reuse the same endpoint resolution and client lifecycle logic everywhere.

17. Sequencing Bug
Definition

The order of operations makes correctness depend on timing.

Detect

Look for:

liveness stamp after persistence instead of before
release finalize before ownership check
leader state set before publication readiness
identity compare before build/checksum available
Failure mode
false resignation
race-dependent flapping
intermittent partial success
Fix rule

Order operations according to invariant, not convenience.

18. Visibility Without Integrity
Definition

Human-readable outputs are reused as machine identity or control input.

Detect

Look for:

--describe output or display strings reused for targeting
IDs derived from display formatting
parsing descriptive text as control identity
Failure mode
cosmetic truncation becomes targeting bug
rollback or selection chooses wrong object
Fix rule

Human-readable output is not a control-plane source of truth.

Typical fix
machine identity must come from canonical structured fields
display strings may include less, but must never be used for selection
Claude Operating Procedure

When something looks wrong, Claude should classify it using this order:

Step 1: Is the truth stale?
stale leader?
stale endpoint?
stale cached client?
old installed-state?
Step 2: Is the truth partial?
version-only?
missing build number?
checksum absent?
unknown node treated as known?
Step 3: Is the truth non-durable?
memory changed, etcd not updated?
persist error ignored?
Step 4: Is the truth unverified?
conditional write with no applied check?
release without ownership proof?
fallback accepted without exact match?
Step 5: Is the control decision non-atomic?
read-then-write race?
uniqueness check without LWT?
Step 6: Is the success predicate too weak?
“exists” instead of “healthy”?
“address changed” instead of “ready”?
Fix Priority Heuristic

Claude should prioritize in this order:

Identity truncation
Ownership / CAS correctness
Persistence gaps
Stale authority
Non-atomic control decisions
Weak successor / weak success predicates
Unsafe remediation
Scaling traps

Because the first five can corrupt control-plane truth directly.

Forbidden Claude Behaviors

Claude must not:

add architecture
add new control flows unless explicitly required
replace strict checks with “fallback for convenience”
invent defaults during recovery
use version-only comparison in control paths
ignore conditional write outcomes
continue healthy after losing proof
One-line doctrine

Claim with proof, persist before fan-out, compare by canonical identity, and fail closed when truth is incomplete.

